<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate beam size for a given span?", answer: "For a simply supported beam with a uniformly distributed load, the maximum bending moment is M = wL squared / 8, where w is the load per unit length and L is the span. The required section modulus is S = M / Fb, where Fb is the allowable bending stress for the beam material. Select a beam whose section modulus equals or exceeds the required value. For example, a 12-foot span carrying 200 plf in Douglas Fir requires a section modulus of about 24 cubic inches, satisfied by a 2x12 or 4x8." },
  { question: "What is the maximum span for a 2x10 beam?", answer: "The maximum span depends on the load and wood species. For Douglas Fir-Larch (No. 2, Fb = 1350 PSI) carrying a typical floor load of 50 plf (dead + live), a single 2x10 (S = 21.39 cubic inches) can span approximately 10-12 feet. For header beams carrying greater loads, the span decreases. Always verify with local building codes, which may require additional safety factors or deflection limits." },
  { question: "What does 'pounds per linear foot' (PLF) mean?", answer: "Pounds per linear foot (PLF) is the total load distributed along each foot of a beam's length. It includes both dead load (the weight of the structure itself, typically 10-20 PLF for residential floors) and live load (people, furniture, and snow, typically 40 PLF for floors and 20-30 PLF for roofs). For a beam supporting a 12-foot-wide floor section, the total PLF would be 12 feet times the per-square-foot load." },
  { question: "What is section modulus and why does it matter?", answer: "Section modulus (S) measures a beam cross-section's resistance to bending, expressed in cubic inches. A higher section modulus means the beam can resist greater bending moments without exceeding the allowable stress. It is calculated as S = bd squared / 6 for rectangular sections, where b is the width and d is the depth. Deeper beams have dramatically higher section moduli because depth is squared in the formula." },
  { question: "What is the difference between LVL and solid lumber beams?", answer: "Laminated Veneer Lumber (LVL) beams are engineered wood products made from thin veneers of wood bonded together under heat and pressure. LVL has an allowable bending stress of approximately 2600 PSI compared to 1350 PSI for Douglas Fir No. 2, meaning LVL can span farther or carry heavier loads in the same size. LVL is also more consistent, with fewer defects like knots and grain deviation that weaken solid lumber." }
]) %>

